close_symbols: uint8 / uint8_t (integer type definition if used in object_ids)
explanation:
Explain why each symbol is required for assessing MISRA dead-code for OS_SelectFdIsSet:

- OS_FdSet (structure definition): The function dereferences Set and reads Set->object_ids. The full struct definition is required to know what other members (if any) are touched/initialized and to determine whether accesses are meaningful or redundant.

- OS_FdSet.object_ids (element type and array length): The return expression indexes object_ids[local_id >> 3] and masks a bit. To determine whether that index/bit access has observable effect (or is redundant/dead), you must know the element type (width signed/unsigned) and the array length (bounds). Out-of-bounds or an array of size 1 used for many fds could change whether the operation is meaningful or undefined — relevant to whether removing it would affect behaviour.

- osal_id_t (typedef): The type and range of the incoming objid can influence OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex behavior and whether certain objid values are ever possible/meaningful; this affects whether the subsequent work is ever executed or could be optimized away.

- osal_index_t (typedef): The type and range of local_id (including signedness and width) affect the shift/index calculation (local_id >> 3, local_id & 0x7) and potential UB or redundant operations; needed to judge if the indexing/bit ops can have any effect.

- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex (function signature and semantics): This call determines whether the bit-test code is reached (via return_code == OS_SUCCESS) and assigns local_id. You must know its precise contract, side-effects, and when it returns success to determine whether the later bit-test ever executes or whether the call itself has side-effects that make removing subsequent operations change behaviour.

- OS_SUCCESS (constant): Used in the success check; its numeric value and semantics are needed to interpret the return_code test and control-flow reachability of the bit-test (dead vs live).

- BUGCHECK (macro definition): The macro is invoked at function entry (BUGCHECK(Set != NULL, false)). Its expansion may perform logging, register state, longjmp/abort, or return the second argument. To determine whether that operation is essential (i.e., removing it would change behaviour) you must inspect its implementation. If BUGCHECK only asserts in debug builds, that affects whether the call is considered dead in production.

- uint8 / uint8_t (integer type definition if used in object_ids): The comment in the function refers to a uint8 object_ids array. Confirming the exact width and unsignedness is necessary to reason about the bit-shift/mask semantics and whether the expression has observable effect.

(These symbols provide the type, bounds, and side-effect information needed to decide if any operations performed by OS_SelectFdIsSet — parameter check, call to OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, and the final bit-test — are actually required for program behaviour, or could be removed without effect.)
